==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|Abderita}}, {{m|la|Abderites}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|Ἀβδηρίτης}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.dəˌɹaɪt/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An inhabitant or native of [[Abdera]], in [[Thrace]].
#* '''1814''', ''The Historical Library of Diodorus the Sicilian'', translated by G. Booth, volume 2, chapter 4, page 27:
#*: To that end they entered the borders of the '''Abderites''' in another part of Thrace, and wasted and spoiled the country {{...}}
# {{label|en|‘the Abderite’}} [[Democritus]], the [[laughing|Laughing]] [[philosopher|Philosopher]].

====Usage notes====
Ancient belief was that "the people of Abdera are fools and madmen" (''stulti et insani Abderitae'').<ref>the Latin and English phrases are quoted as they appear in Robert Burton's ''The Anatomy of Melancholy'', volume 1 (2010)</ref>

